<section class="SP">
<div class="W">
  <div class="IB C"><div class="ibl">📖 For Learners — What is Reconnaissance?</div><p>Before any real cyberattack, the attacker needs a complete map of the target. Reconnaissance (recon) is the process of scanning a network to discover: which machines exist, what services are running, what software versions are installed, and what known vulnerabilities (CVEs) those versions have. Think of it like casing a building before a heist — you need to know every door and window before picking which one to enter. In professional pentesting, this is called the "information gathering" or "discovery" phase of the PTES (Penetration Testing Execution Standard).</p></div>
  <div class="DTL">
    <div>
      <div class="eye B" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Step A — Host Discovery (Ping Sweep)</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Finding all <span class="tb">live machines</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">The first command identifies every active machine on the 192.168.64.0/24 subnet. The <strong>-sn flag</strong> (no port scan) simply pings each IP to check if it's alive. This generates very little traffic and is difficult to detect without a properly configured IDS/IPS.</p>
      <pre class="CB"><span class="CC"># Step A — Run from Kali Linux terminal</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo nmap</span> <span class="FLG">-sn</span> <span class="VAL">192.168.64.0/24</span>

<span class="CC"># Output — 3 hosts found on the port network segment:</span>
<span class="OK">Nmap scan report for 192.168.64.1</span>  <span class="OUT">→ Gateway (router)</span>
<span class="OK">Nmap scan report for 192.168.64.2</span>  <span class="OUT">→ Ubuntu SCADA server ← PRIMARY TARGET</span>
<span class="OK">Nmap scan report for 192.168.64.4</span>  <span class="OUT">→ Kali Linux (our machine)</span>

<span class="OK">3 hosts up</span> <span class="OUT">| Scan completed in 2.11 seconds</span></pre>

      <div class="eye B" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step B — Deep Service & Version Scan</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Identifying every <span class="tb">open door</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Now we run an aggressive full scan on the target (192.168.64.2). Each flag has a specific purpose: <strong>-sV</strong> probes each open port to identify the exact software and version, <strong>-sC</strong> runs Nmap's default scripts (like checking for open proxies, anonymous FTP, etc.), <strong>-O</strong> fingerprints the operating system, <strong>-A</strong> enables aggressive detection. The output is saved for the CVE analysis script.</p>
      <pre class="CB A"><span class="CC"># Step B — Full version + script + OS detection scan</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo nmap</span> <span class="FLG">-sV -sC -O -A</span> <span class="VAL">192.168.64.2</span> <span class="FLG">-oN</span> <span class="VAL">~/recon_lab/scan_scada.txt</span>

<span class="CC"># Discovered services — Complete results:</span>
<span class="FLG">22/tcp    open  ssh</span>    <span class="OK">OpenSSH 9.6p1 Ubuntu 4ubuntu0.3</span>
<span class="FLG">80/tcp    open  http</span>   <span class="OK">Apache httpd 2.4.58 (Ubuntu)</span>
                        <span class="WRN">|_http-server-header: Apache/2.4.58 (Ubuntu)</span>
<span class="FLG">3128/tcp  open  http</span>   <span class="OK">Squid http proxy 6.13</span>
                        <span class="ERR">|_http-open-proxy: Potentially OPEN proxy ← UNEXPECTED!</span>
<span class="FLG">5020/tcp  open  ftp?</span>   <span class="OK">Python SCADA server (custom)</span>
                        <span class="ERR">|_ No authentication banner detected</span>

<span class="OUT">OS: Linux 4.15 - 5.19 (Ubuntu 24) | 96% confidence</span>
<span class="OUT">Scan duration: 13.62 seconds</span></pre>

      <div class="IB A"><div class="ibl">⚠️ Unexpected Critical Finding — Open Proxy on :3128</div><p>Nmap's default scripts automatically flagged Squid proxy on port 3128 as an open proxy — meaning it accepts connections from anyone without authentication. This was NOT expected before the scan. An open proxy in port infrastructure can be used to: (1) route attack traffic anonymously through the port's own IP, (2) access internal resources not directly reachable, (3) bypass firewall rules by pivoting. This is a perfect example of why automated recon matters — you find what you don't know you're looking for.</p></div>

      <div class="eye B" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step C — Automated CVE Mapping</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Turning versions into <span class="tr">exploitable vulnerabilities</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">A custom Python script reads the Nmap output file, parses each service name and version, then cross-references them against a local CVE database (mirroring NVD — National Vulnerability Database). This is what professional tools like OpenVAS, Nessus, and Qualys do — except here every line of logic is visible and explainable.</p>
      <pre class="CB V"><span class="CC"># Step C — Run CVE analyzer</span>
<span class="CMD">python3</span> <span class="VAL">~/recon_lab/recon_analyzer.py</span>

<span class="CC"># Analysis output:</span>
<span class="ERR">► CVE-2024-6387   SSH 22   CVSS 9.8  CRITICAL  RegreSSHion — Unauth RCE</span>
<span class="ERR">► CVE-2024-38474  HTTP 80  CVSS 9.1  CRITICAL  Apache mod_rewrite code exec</span>
<span class="ERR">► SCADA-001       5020     CVSS 10.0 CRITICAL  Zero auth on SCADA interface</span>
<span class="ERR">► SCADA-002       5020     CVSS 9.5  CRITICAL  Plaintext SCADA protocol</span>
<span class="WRN">► CVE-2024-38473  HTTP 80  CVSS 7.5  HIGH      Apache auth bypass</span>
<span class="WRN">► CVE-2023-45802  HTTP 80  CVSS 7.5  HIGH      HTTP/2 stream reset DoS</span>
<span class="WRN">► CVE-2024-45802  Squid    CVSS 7.5  HIGH      Open proxy + crash vector</span>
<span class="WRN">► CVE-2023-51385  SSH 22   CVSS 6.5  HIGH      SSH command injection</span>
<span class="OUT">► CVE-2024-37894  Squid    CVSS 6.3  MEDIUM    Internal resource access</span>

<span class="OK">═══════════════════════════════════════════════════</span>
<span class="OK">SUMMARY: 9 vulnerabilities | 4 CRITICAL | Risk: CRITICAL</span>
<span class="OK">PDF report generated: rapport_reconnaissance_tangermed.pdf</span></pre>

      <div class="SIEM">
        <div class="SIEMH"><span class="SIEMT">siem_recon.py — Detection Log</span><span class="SIEML"><div class="npulse"></div>ANALYSIS COMPLETE</span></div>
        <div class="SIEMB">
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:01</span><span class="SLEV slI">[INFO]</span><span class="SLM">Nmap scan started against 192.168.64.2 from 192.168.64.4</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:14</span><span class="SLEV slI">[INFO]</span><span class="SLM">4 services discovered — parsing version data</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:14</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">SCADA port 5020 — ZERO authentication (CVSS 10.0)</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:14</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">CVE-2024-6387 RegreSSHion — OpenSSH 9.6p1 (CVSS 9.8)</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:14</span><span class="SLEV slH">[HIGH]</span><span class="SLM">Open proxy detected on Squid 6.13 port 3128</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">13:42:15</span><span class="SLEV slG">[DONE]</span><span class="SLM">PDF report saved → rapport_reconnaissance_tangermed.pdf</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="IB G"><div class="ibl">🔵 Blue Team Lesson — What should be done?</div><p>The entire recon output reveals a catastrophic misconfiguration: a SCADA port with <strong>CVSS 10.0</strong> (the maximum possible score) exposed on the network with zero authentication. The open proxy on :3128 should be restricted to internal IPs only. All CVEs have patches available — a proper patch management process would eliminate 7 of 9 vulnerabilities immediately. The SCADA port requires a complete re-architecture with authentication, encryption, and network segmentation.</p></div>
    </div>
