<span class="OK">═══════════════════════════════════════</span>
<span class="OK">TOTAL CAPTURES: 89 credentials | Attacker IP: 192.168.64.4</span></div>

      <div class="eye R" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step D — Fail2ban Progressive Banning</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">The <span class="tg">escalating shield</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Fail2ban monitors <strong>/var/log/auth.log</strong> in real time. After 5 failed SSH attempts in 60 seconds, it adds an iptables firewall rule to block the attacker's IP. The advanced configuration uses <strong>bantime.increment</strong> — every time the same IP is banned again, the duration doubles. This exponential backoff discourages persistent attackers far more effectively than a flat ban duration.</p>
      <div class="BAN">
        <div class="BANI bi0"><span class="BN">Ban #1</span><span class="BD">5 failed SSH attempts from 192.168.64.4 detected in 60s</span><span class="BV ta">1 min</span></div>
        <div class="BANI bi1"><span class="BN">Ban #2</span><span class="BD">Attacker returned after ban expiry — banned again (×2)</span><span class="BV tr">2 min</span></div>
        <div class="BANI bi2"><span class="BN">Ban #3</span><span class="BD">Third attempt — exponential escalation applied (×2)</span><span class="BV tr">4 min</span></div>
      </div>
      <pre class="CB G"><span class="CC"># /etc/fail2ban/jail.local — Progressive configuration</span>
<span class="FLG">[DEFAULT]</span>
<span class="OK">bantime.increment = true</span>     <span class="CC">← enables exponential escalation</span>
<span class="OK">bantime.factor    = 2</span>        <span class="CC">← doubles the ban time each recurrence</span>
<span class="OK">bantime.maxtime   = 3600</span>     <span class="CC">← cap at 1 hour maximum</span>
<span class="FLG">[sshd]</span>
<span class="VAL">maxretry = 5</span>                 <span class="CC">← trigger after 5 failures</span>
<span class="VAL">findtime = 60</span>                <span class="CC">← within 60 seconds window</span>
<span class="VAL">bantime  = 60</span>                <span class="CC">← base ban: 1 minute</span></pre>

      <div class="eye R" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step E — SIEM Alerts Generated</div>
      <div class="AL">
        <div class="AE"><div class="AEL LM">L5</div><div class="AER" style="color:var(--amber);">Rule 200001</div><div class="AEM">SSH connection attempt — 192.168.64.4 → portuser @ 192.168.64.2:22</div></div>
        <div class="AE"><div class="AEL LC">L10</div><div class="AER" style="color:var(--red);">Rule 200002</div><div class="AEM">BRUTE FORCE DETECTED — 5 SSH failures in &lt;60s from 192.168.64.4</div></div>
        <div class="AE"><div class="AEL LG">L7</div><div class="AER" style="color:var(--green);">Rule 200003</div><div class="AEM">FAIL2BAN — IP 192.168.64.4 automatically banned (ban #1 — 1 min)</div></div>
        <div class="AE"><div class="AEL LC">L10</div><div class="AER" style="color:var(--red);">Rule 200004</div><div class="AEM">SSH INTRUSION — Successful login: <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="a2d2cdd0d6d7d1c7d0e2939b908c93949a8c94968c90">[email&#160;protected]</a> from 192.168.64.4</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="IB G"><div class="ibl">🔵 Blue Team Lesson</div><p>This simulation proves that <strong>password-based SSH authentication is fundamentally weak</strong> in critical infrastructure. The fix is not a stronger password — it's replacing password auth entirely with SSH key pairs (RSA 4096 or Ed25519) and disabling PasswordAuthentication in sshd_config. With key-based auth, brute force becomes mathematically impossible. MFA (TOTP) adds a second layer.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="SB">
