<section class="SP">
<div class="W">
  <div class="IB C"><div class="ibl">📖 For Learners — What is Lateral Movement & Privilege Escalation?</div><p>After gaining initial SSH access as a low-privilege user (portuser), the attacker's goal is to <strong>escalate privileges</strong> (become root/administrator) and <strong>move laterally</strong> (reach systems not directly accessible). In this simulation, a single misconfigured sudo rule — allowing portuser to run python3 as root with no password — turns a limited shell into complete system control in under one second. This is one of the most common real-world attack patterns: initial access is low-privilege, but misconfigured permissions create the path to total compromise.</p></div>
  <div class="DTL">
    <div>
      <div class="STATS">
        <div class="SC"><span class="SCV tc">6</span><span class="SCL">Attack Phases</span></div>
        <div class="SC"><span class="SCV tr">1 cmd</span><span class="SCL">To Root Access</span></div>
