<section class="SP">
<div class="W">
  <div class="eye G rv">Defensive Mechanisms Deployed</div>
  <h2 class="DM rv" style="margin-bottom:8px;">3 layers, <span class="tg">100%</span> detection rate</h2>
  <p class="BM rv" style="max-width:580px;">Every attack met a defensive response. The key insight: <strong>defense in depth</strong> means no single layer needs to be perfect — they complement each other. An attacker who bypasses Fail2ban still gets caught by the honeypot. An attack that evades the honeypot triggers SIEM rules. Layered defense works.</p>
  <div class="DEFG rv">
    <div class="DC D0"><span class="DCico">🍯</span><h4>SSH Honeypot</h4><p>Python + Paramiko fake SSH server on port 2222. Authenticates the SSH handshake but never grants access. Silently captures every credential attempted. 89 attacker credentials harvested in Simulation 2 with full IP and timestamp logging.</p></div>
    <div class="DC D1"><span class="DCico">🚫</span><h4>Fail2ban Progressive</h4><p>After 5 SSH failures in 60 seconds, IP is blocked via iptables. bantime.increment doubles the ban duration on each recurrence: 1 min → 2 min → 4 min. Exponential backoff discourages persistent automated attacks without blocking legitimate users.</p></div>
    <div class="DC D2"><span class="DCico">📊</span><h4>Python SIEM Custom</h4><p>Monitors /var/log/auth.log and /var/log/scada_server.log in real time. 8 detection rules covering SSH brute force, SCADA anomalies, ARP spoofing, and lateral movement events. All 4 simulations detected in under 1 second each.</p></div>
    <div class="DC D3"><span class="DCico">🗺️</span><h4>CVE Auto-Mapping</h4><p>Python script correlates Nmap scan results with CVE database to generate instant vulnerability assessment. Produces PDF reports with CVSS scores, impact analysis, and remediation priorities — exactly what a professional VA report contains.</p></div>
    <div class="DC D4"><span class="DCico">🔍</span><h4>Forensic Analysis</h4><p>Complete post-incident investigation using last, auth.log grep, crontab inspection, and authorized_keys review. Both backdoors identified and removed within minutes. Full attack timeline reconstructed from logs — 100% forensic coverage.</p></div>
    <div class="DC D5"><span class="DCico">🔗</span><h4>Unified Kill Chain</h4><p>All 4 simulations feed into the same log infrastructure. SSH alerts from Sim 2 and SCADA anomalies from Sim 3 coexist in the same SIEM — exactly like a real SOC. The correlation between events is what reveals the full APT picture.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top:32px;" class="rv">
    <div class="eye G">Consolidated Results — What We Proved</div>
    <h2 class="DM" style="margin-bottom:24px;">Key <span class="tg">findings & proofs</span></h2>
    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px;">
      <div class="PROOT P0"><h5>tangermed2024 cracked in 4 attempts — not millions</h5><p>OSINT contextual wordlists are exponentially more efficient than generic lists. Password policies must go beyond complexity — service accounts in SCADA environments must use SSH key authentication only.</p></div>
      <div class="PROOT P1"><h5>89 attacker credentials captured in honeypot — full intelligence</h5><p>The attacker had no idea they were in a trap after port 22 was blocked. Honeypots convert attackers into intelligence sources. Every credential they try reveals their wordlist strategy.</p></div>
      <div class="PROOT P2"><h5>CVSS 10.0 vulnerability found with a 13-second Nmap scan</h5><p>The most dangerous vulnerability in the lab required zero exploitation skill — just running Nmap and seeing that port 5020 has no authentication. Misconfiguration is more dangerous than missing patches.</p></div>
      <div class="PROOT P3"><h5>Root access in 1 command from a low-privilege user</h5><p>A single misconfigured sudo rule (python3 NOPASSWD) turned a restricted portuser account into complete root control in under 10 seconds. Principle of least privilege is non-negotiable in critical infrastructure.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top:32px;" class="rv">
    <div class="eye G">Concrete Recommendations</div>
    <h2 class="DM" style="margin-bottom:8px;">8 fixes that would have <span class="tg">stopped everything</span></h2>
    <p class="BM" style="max-width:560px;margin-bottom:0;">Each recommendation directly addresses a demonstrated vulnerability. Implementation priority is ordered by CVSS score — highest risk first.</p>
    <div class="RECG">
      <div class="RCC RC0"><div class="RCBDG">CRITICAL — SCADA-001</div><h4>Authenticate SCADA</h4><p>Replace custom TCP protocol with Modbus/TLS or OPC-UA. Implement mutual TLS authentication. Deploy an OT-aware firewall (Fortinet FortiGate OT, Cisco IE). Zero auth on an industrial interface is the single most dangerous finding in this entire lab.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC0"><div class="RCBDG">CRITICAL — Sim 2</div><h4>Patch CVE-2024-6387</h4><p>RegreSSHion (CVSS 9.8) requires patching within 72 hours. Implement automated CVE monitoring against NVD for all services. Set SLAs: Critical CVEs patched in 72h, High CVEs in 7 days, Medium in 30 days. No exceptions for SCADA environments.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC0"><div class="RCBDG">CRITICAL — Sim 4</div><h4>Remove sudo NOPASSWD</h4><p>Remove all NOPASSWD sudo rules for service accounts immediately. Apply principle of least privilege: portuser should have NO sudo access. Use systemd services with appropriate user permissions for SCADA scripts. Audit all sudoers files across the port network.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC1"><div class="RCBDG">HIGH — Sim 2</div><h4>SSH Keys + MFA</h4><p>Disable PasswordAuthentication in /etc/ssh/sshd_config for all SCADA servers. Deploy Ed25519 or RSA-4096 key pairs for all admin accounts. Add TOTP (Google Authenticator or Duo) as a second factor. Brute force becomes mathematically impossible with key-only auth.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC1"><div class="RCBDG">HIGH — Sim 1</div><h4>Network Segmentation</div><p>Deploy dedicated VLANs for OT/SCADA networks. No IT device should have direct access to SCADA ports. Firewall rules: deny all → permit only (allowlist). The fact that Kali could reach port 5020 directly from the same network is a fundamental architecture failure.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC1"><div class="RCBDG">HIGH — Sim 1</div><h4>Close Open Proxy</h4><p>Disable anonymous access on Squid proxy or restrict to specific authenticated IPs. An open proxy on port infrastructure is a free anonymization service for attackers. Configure Squid with ACLs, authentication (NTLM/Kerberos), and SSL bump inspection.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC2"><div class="RCBDG">MEDIUM — Defense</div><h4>Permanent Honeypots</h4><p>Move real SSH to a non-standard port (e.g., 2200). Keep honeypot on port 22. Deploy Conpot for ICS/SCADA honeypotting on port 5020. Use T-Pot or OpenCanary for full honeypot infrastructure. Convert attackers into intelligence sources continuously.</p></div>
      <div class="RCC RC2"><div class="RCBDG">MEDIUM — SIEM</div><h4>24/7 OT SOC</h4><p>Deploy Wazuh, Splunk, or Microsoft Sentinel with OT-specific rule packs (Modbus, DNP3, IEC 60870-5-104). Train a dedicated SOC team with both IT and OT expertise. Implement automated incident response playbooks — SIEM alerts must trigger automated containment within 60 seconds.</p></div>
